{{Infobox person |name = Xhanti Charles Sebe |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_name = |birth_date = |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |death_cause = |resting_place = |resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} --> |residence = |nationality = |ethnicity = |citizenship = |known_for = Ciskei state security head, rebel and murder victim |alma_mater = |occupation = |title = |networth = |religion = |spouse = |parents = |signature = |footnotes = }} Lt. General '''Xhanti Charles Sebe'''<ref name="drumFamousQuots">{{cite web|url=http://www.museum.za.net/index.php/imvubu-newsletter/105-lt-gen-charles-xhanti-sebe-a-few-famous-quotes|title=Lt. Gen. Charles Xhanti Sebe: A few Famous Quotes|website=www.museum.za.net}}</ref>, was leader of the [[Ciskei Defence Force]]- the military of the [[Bantustan]] of [[Ciskei]], and its Director of State Security. A former security branch policeman, he later joined the [[South Africa]]n [[Bureau of State Security]] (B.O.S.S.) before founding the Ciskei state security apparatus.<ref name="trcV2Ch5">{{cite web|url=http://sabctrc.saha.org.za/reports/volume2/chapter5/subsection20.htm|title=Truth Commission - Special Report - TRC Final Report - Volume 2, Section 1, Chapter|website=sabctrc.saha.org.za}}</ref>
Described as having created a [[police state]] in Ciskei,<ref name="nytMisery">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/09/25/magazine/misery-in-a-south-african-homeland.html|title=MISERY IN A SOUTH AFRICAN 'HOMELAND'|first=Joseph|last=Lelyveld|publisher=}}</ref><ref name="hrwSA1991-3">{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/1991/southafrica3/|title=South Africa: Ciskei: Ten Years on Human Rights and the Fiction of “Independence” (Human Rights Watch Report, December 20, 1991)|website=www.hrw.org}}</ref> and being perceived as its ''de facto'' ruler<ref name="trcv2ch5s17">{{cite web|url=http://sabctrc.saha.org.za/reports/volume2/chapter5/subsection17.htm?t=+sebe++charles&tab=report|title=Truth Commission - Special Report - TRC Final Report - Volume 2, Section 1, Chapter|website=sabctrc.saha.org.za}}</ref>, he was the brother of [[Lennox Sebe]]. He was subsequently arrested by his brother's government, and sentenced to prison by the Ciskei government for [[incitement]],<ref name="saHistoryImprisoned">{{cite web|url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/dated-event/former-commander-armed-forces-ciskei-major-general-charles-sebe-imprisoned|title=Former commander of the armed forces of the Ciskei, Major-General Charles Sebe is imprisoned|first=|last=sahoboss|date=16 March 2011|publisher=}}</ref><ref name="trcThoba">http://www.justice.gov.za/trc/decisions/1997/970414_thoba.htm</ref> but was rescued from jail by white [[mercenaries]],<ref name="nytPuzzleOdds">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/10/20/world/pretoria-puzzle-homelands-at-odds.html|title=PRETORIA PUZZLE: 'HOMELANDS' AT ODDS|first=Alan Cowell and Special To the New York|last=Times|publisher=}}</ref> and escaped to the nearby Bantustan of [[Transkei]], where he began an organisation that aimed to overthrow his brother's government.<ref name="trcSapa1996">{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov.za/trc/media%5C1996%5C9607/s960729c.htm|title=SAPA - 29 Jul 96 - FORMER CISKEI RULER'S SON WAS MOST FEARED IN|website=