Charles Sebe was lured back to Ciskei in an operation orchestrated by South African security forces<ref name="trcv3ch2-29">{{cite web|url=http://sabctrc.saha.org.za/reports/volume3/chapter2/subsection29.htm?t=+sebe++charles&tab=report|title=Truth Commission - Special Report - TRC Final Report - Volume 3, Section 1, Chapter|website=sabctrc.saha.org.za}}</ref><ref name="csMonitorDivideRle"/> in 1991, during the rule of [[Oupa Gqozo]], and, having been wounded in an ambush which killed an associate, was the subject of a manhunt, and he was subsequently was shot to death in cold blood<ref name="mgOupa">{{cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2004-04-07-oupa-gqozo-an-officer-and-a-gentleman|title=Oupa Gqozo: An 'officer and a gentleman'|first=Ben|last=Maclennan|publisher=}}</ref> by the Ciskei Security forces.<ref name="hrwSA1991-3"/><ref name="csMonitorDivideRle">{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1992/0909/09061.html|title=Pretoria's `Divide and Rule' Strategy in Ciskei|date=9 September 1992|publisher=|via=Christian Science Monitor}}</ref><ref name="cWhiteGqozo"">http://letras.comp.filos.unam.mx/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/ColinWhite_TheRuleOfBrigadierOupaGqozoInCiskei.pdf</ref><ref name="upiCoupKilled">{{cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1991/01/28/South-Africa-Second-alleged-Ciskei-coup-plotter-killed/5520665038800/|title=South Africa: Second alleged Ciskei coup plotter killed|publisher=}}</ref> Gqozo was tried in 1993 for the murder, by the [[Ciskei Supreme Court]], and, together with his co-accused, Sergeant-Major Thozamile Veliti, Gqozo was acquitted.<ref name="yWorldTodayInHistory">{{cite web|url=http://yworld.co.za/yworld/tih/today_in_history?search-day=9&search-year=15&search-month=11|title=Today In History - YFM - Yona Ke Yona|website=yworld.co.za}}</ref>
