{{POV|date=August 2016}} {{Infobox civilian attack | title = Leftist errors | partof = [[World War II in Yugoslavia]] | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | map = | map_size = | map_alt = | map_caption = | location ={{tree list}} * [[Axis occupation of Yugoslavia|Axis-occupied Yugoslavia]] ** [[Montenegro]] ** [[Herzegovina]] ** [[Serbia]] **{{Tree list/final branch}} to a lesser extent: [[Croatia]] and [[Slovenia]] {{tree list/end}} | target = | coordinates = | date = July 1941{{dubious|date=April 2014}} – Spring 1942 | time = | timezone = | type = | fatalities = {{tree list}} * 1941–42: ** Herzegovina: 500 **{{Tree list/final branch}} Montenegro: 500–624 {{tree list/end}} | injuries = | victims = | perps = <!-- or | perp = --> | perpetrator = [[Communist Party of Yugoslavia]] | susperps = <!-- or | susperp = --> | weapons = | numparts = <!-- or | numpart = --> | dfens = <!-- or | dfen = --> | motive = }}
'''Leftist errors''' ({{lang-sh|leva/lijeva skretanja}}) was a term used by the [[Communist Party of Yugoslavia]] (CPY) to describe radical policies and strategies – described as the '''Red Terror''' by others – pursued by self-described [[Left-wing politics|left-wing]] elements among the party and [[Yugoslav Partisans|partisan units]] during [[World War II]], mostly in [[Montenegro]], [[Herzegovina]] and [[Serbia]], as well as to a lesser extent in [[Croatia]] and [[Slovenia]].{{sfn|Banac|1990|p=89}}<ref>{{harvnb|Goldstein|2008|p=287}} {{lang|hr|"Bila je to akcija nazvana kasnije „lijeva skretanja" ponajviše provođena u Bosni i Crnoj Gori, a mnogo manje u Hrvatskoj."}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=NIN: nedeljne informativne novine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ft8xAQAAIAAJ|year=2002|publisher=Politika|page=4<!-- |quote=...тзв. лева скретања, односно убиства „кулака" у Херцеговини, Црној Гори, Босни и Срему, злочини извршени у тзв. Ужичкој републици и на крају масовна стрељања у Србији и Београду октобра 1944. године. -->}}</ref> From 1941-42, these areas saw mass executions, burning of villages and confiscation of property,<ref name="Morrison2009">{{cite book|last=Morrison|first=Kenneth|title=Montenegro: a modern history|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xKMtAQAAIAAJ|year=2009|publisher=I.B. Tauris|isbn=978-1-84511-710-8|page=55}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=NIN: nedeljne informativne novine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ft8xAQAAIAAJ|year=2002|publisher=Politika|page=4<!-- |quote=...тзв. лева скретања, односно убиства „кулака" у Херцеговини, Црној Гори, Босни и Срему, злочини извршени у тзв. Ужичкој републици и на крају масовна стрељања у Србији и Београду октобра 1944. године. -->}}</ref> motivated both by partisan fears of a "[[fifth column]]" and [[class conflict]].{{sfn|Hurem|1972|p=155}} As a result of these actions by the communists, many villagers from Eastern Herzegovina and Montenegro, who were far from being collaborators or [[kulak]]s, joined [[Chetnik]] forces en masse.{{sfn|Banac|1988|p=82<!-- |ps=: "In the end, the red terror of 1941–1942 turned out to be a serious mistake. ... Terrorized peasants who were anything but collaborators or kulaks swelled the Chetnik ranks in Montenegro and Eastern Herzegovina." --> }} The Communist Party of Yugoslavia condemned actions undertaken during the period and punished several local commanders.
== Name == This policy was also referred to as '''Leftist deviation''' or '''Left-wing deviation''',<ref name="PrestonPartridge2002">{{cite book|last1=Preston|first1=Paul|authorlink1=Paul Preston|last2=Partridge|first2=Michael|last3=Smyth|first3=Denis|authorlink3=Denis Smyth |title=British documents on foreign affairs: reports and papers from the Foreign Office confidential print. From 1945 through 1950. Europe / editor, Denis Smyth|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E8yQAAAAMAAJ|year=2002|publisher=University Publications of America|isbn=978-1-55655-769-9|page=76}}</ref> '''Left Errors'''{{sfn|Banac|1988|p=82}} or '''sectarian deviations'''. In [[Titoism|Titoist]] [[dogma]] after [[World War II]] this policy was referred to as the "Mistakes of the left" <ref name="Morrison2009">{{cite book|last=Morrison|first=Kenneth|title=Montenegro: a modern history|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xKMtAQAAIAAJ|year=2009|publisher=I.B. Tauris|isbn=978-1-84511-710-8|page=55}}</ref> or "left deviations" while the others referred to it as '''"Red Terror"'''.{{sfn|Lampe|2000|p=214}} This policy is sometimes referred to as the "Second Stage".{{sfn|Banac|1988|p=82}} [[Karl Marx]] believed that revolution has two stages: bourgeois-democratic and [[Proletarian revolution|proletarian]]. He believed that in the second stage the proletarian revolution has to turn against its allies from the first stage.<ref>{{cite book|last=Vukcevich|first=Bosko S.|title=Diverse forces in Yugoslavia: 1941-1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FJJpAAAAMAAJ|year=1990|publisher=Authors Unlimited|isbn=978-1-55666-053-5|page=390}}</ref>
==Background== [[File:Josip Broz Tito uniform portrait.jpg|thumbnail|140px|[[Josip Broz Tito|Tito]] formulated the leftist strategy of the [[Communist Party of Yugoslavia|CPY]] in October 1940]] [[Josip Broz Tito|Tito]] was the main protagonist of the leftist deviations.{{Sfn|Petranović|1992|p=307<!-- |ps=: Glavni skretač u „levo" bio je Josip Broz Tito, o čemu govore i njegove inicijative 1941-1942. i 1943. godine" -->}} Tito was well known as leftist who was against any arrangements with non-[[Communism|communists]]. His formal appointment as general secretary of the [[Communist Party of Yugoslavia]] (CPY) was confirmed in October 1940 during the Fifth Land Conference of the CPY in [[Zagreb]]. At this conference Tito formulated the leftist strategy of the CPY as focused on revolutionary seizure of power in the country in order to organize [[Soviet]]-style administrative organization in [[Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Joel Krieger|title=The Oxford Companion to Politics of the World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2wd30pXJxpYC&pg=PA838|date=2 August 2001|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-511739-4|page=838|quote=...in 1939 and received internal confirmation at the Fifth Land Conference of the KP, held in Zagreb, in October 1940. Tito was already noted as a leftist who put little stock in Popular Front arrangements with non-Communists. Moreover, he was federalist, seeing the solution of the nationality question in Yugoslavia in Soviet style federation. This led him to complain against Soviet pleas for cooperation with anti-Communist and Greater Serbian [[Chetnik]]s during the war and prompted him to emphasize the revolutionary seizure of power.}}</ref><ref name="inc1998">{{cite book|author=Encyclopædia Britannica, inc|title=The New Encyclopædia Britannica|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FFtYAAAAMAAJ|year=1998|publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica|isbn=978-0-85229-633-2|page=804|quote=At Fifth Land Conference of CPY, as underground minicongres held in Zagreb in October 1940, Tito sketched CPY's leftist strategy, which focused the party on armed insurrection and on Soviet style federalist solution to Yugoslavia. }}</ref>{{sfn|Banac|1988|p=77<!-- |ps=: "The political line of the Fifth Conference was strictly leftist..." --> }}
In July 1941, after the beginning of the Second World War, the Communist Politburo adopted the strategy which insisted that the Partisans should aim to create "liberated territories", cleared of enemies. According to the instructions of the Poliburo, such territories were to be administered by the communists in a state-like manner so the local population would be exposed to the ideas and practice of the [[socialism]]. On the territories that came under their control the communists adopted many leftist policies including radical socialism. This antagonized many peasants in Serbia, Montenegro and Herzegovina.{{sfn|Haug|2012|p=68<!-- |ps=: "In July 1941, the Politburo adopted a strategy advocating that the Partisans should aim to create operational bases known as "liberated territories", which would be cleared of enemies...." --> }} Laziness was punished as desertion, peasants were punished with high taxes or [[forced labor]] if their houses were not tidy or if they got [[Louse|lice]].{{sfn|Banac|1990|p=89}} The Yugoslav communists suspended the instructions not to reach the second stage (the revolution) given by the [[Comintern]] in June 1941. Because they ignored instructions from Moscow the leadership of CPY could not find a modus vivendi with other resistance movement, the Chetniks of Mihajlović, because they could put in danger communist revolutionary action.{{sfn|Petranović|2002|p=68<!-- |ps=: "The KPJ suspended the instruction received from the Comintern in June 1941 not to get down to the second stage, that is to revolution....Namely, by ignoring the instruction from Moscow, the Communist leadership could not work out sincerely a modus vivendi with the other resistance movement in Serbia, the Chetniks of D. Mihajlović, which could jeopardize their revolutionary action. " --> }} That is why Tito rejected Soviet pleas to cooperate with Chetniks and insisted on carrying on with the communist revolution.<ref>{{cite book|author=Joel Krieger|title=The Oxford Companion to Politics of the World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2wd30pXJxpYC&pg=PA838|date=2 August 2001|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-511739-4|page=838|quote= This led him to complain against Soviet pleas for cooperation with anti-Communist and Greater Serbian Chetniks during the war and prompted him to emphasize the revolutionary seizure of power.}}</ref>
==Montenegro== [[File:Moša Pijade.jpg|thumbnail|left|150px|Moša Pijade, one of the main protagonists of Leftist errors in Montenegro]] In June 1941 the Regional Committee of CPY for Montenegro, Boka and Sandžak issued a proclamation inviting people to "final liquidation of capitalist system".<ref name="Лакић1981a">{{cite book|last=Лакић|first=Зоран|title=Народна власт у Црној Гори 1941–1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=emwNAAAAIAAJ|year=1981|publisher=Обод|page=87<!-- |quote=... у документима Покрајинског комитета КПЈ за Црну Гору, Боку и Санџак. У његовом јунском прогласу 1941 народ се позива на "коначан обрачун са капиталистичким системом." -->}}</ref> Leftist errors policy was pursued in Montenegro since August while its intensity was increased since September 1941.<ref name="Лакић1981b">{{cite book|last=Лакић|first=Зоран|title=Народна власт у Црној Гори 1941–1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=emwNAAAAIAAJ|year=1981|publisher=Обод|page=247<!-- |quote= Иако су такозвана „лијева скретања" у Црној Гори почела августа а била чешћа од септембра 1941. године, ... -->}}</ref>{{sfn|Strugar|1997|p=144<!-- |ps=: "Нови курс КПЈ, касније назван „леве грешке" или „лева скретања", довешће до грубих обрачуна и егзекуција над стварним и измишљеним противницима у Санцаку, Босни и Херцеговини, Црној Гори, Србији, што ће изазвати ..." -->}}{{Verify source|date=March 2014}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Đorđević|first=Milinko|title=Sedam levih godina|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZlwtAQAAIAAJ|year=2000|publisher=Naš dom|page=14|quote=Практична последица овог става су учестале ликвидације "непријатеља", које су "отпочеле у августу, а од средине септембра су биле доста честе", како то произилази из извештаја Покрајинског Комитета КПЈ за Црну Гору, Боку и Санџак од 8 Децембра 1941}}</ref>{{sfn|Haug|2012|p=68<!-- |ps=: "In July 1941, the Politburo adopted a strategy advocating that the Partisans should aim to create operational bases known as "liberated territories", which would be cleared of enemies...." --> }} This extremist policy was pursued by the Partisans in Montenegro under the influence of [[Milovan Đilas]] and [[Moša Pijade]].<ref name="Goulding2002">{{cite book|last=Goulding|first=Daniel J.|title=Liberated Cinema: The Yugoslav Experience, 1945–2001|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z6KOL-DnxIkC&pg=PA14|year=2002|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=0-253-34210-4|page=14|quote=Under the influence of Milovan Djilas and the Marxist intellectual Mosa Pijade, however, the Partisan forces in Montenegro followed an extremist political line}}</ref> After the initial success of the [[Uprising in Montenegro (1941)|Uprising in Montenegro]] communists seized control of almost all the territory of Montenegro and began to fight against their class enemies. The substantial percentage of population of Montenegro supported Chetniks because they were afraid of the "red terror".<ref name="KlemenčičŽagar2004">{{cite book|last1=Klemenčič|first1=Matjaž|last2=Žagar|first2=Mitja|title=The Former Yugoslavia's Diverse Peoples: A Reference Sourcebook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ORSMBFwjAKcC&pg=PA176|year=2004|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-57607-294-3|page=176|quote=In a very short period of time almost all the territory of Montenegro (with exception of some important cities) fell into hands of the communists. But the communist [sic] made mistake and started to fight against their class enemy (i.e. members of the Montenegrin bourgeoisie) which made them weaker. The Italians resumed their attacks and by the mid August 1941 had again enforced their control in Montenegro....Out of fear of the “red-terror”, a significant percentage of Montenegrins started to cooperate with the Chetniks, who started to attack Partisans..... The Partisan movement strengthen again in Autumn.}}</ref> Despite instructions to minimize the revolutionary side of their policies, the leaders of Montenegrin Partisans introduced "Soviet elements" in the summer of 1941, during the Uprising in Montenegro, because they perceived the uprising as the first stage of the communist revolution.{{sfn|Haug|2012|p=68<!-- |ps=: "Despite instructions to play down revolutionary aspects of their policies, two leading Montenegrin members of the Politburo, Đilas and Milutinović (both among the most radical leftist in the party membership) introduced what is referred to as "Soviet elements" during the uprising in Montenegro in the summer of 1941" --> }}
In mid-August 1941, Đilas wrote a letter to the Regional Committee of Yugoslav Communist Party for Montenegro, Boka and Sandžak and recommended an isolation and destruction of the [[fifth column]]. He emphasized that tolerance and inactivity of communists toward spies is a crime equal to treason. At the end of August 1941 the Regional Committee issued a directive which follows the recommendations of Đilas and insists on cleansing of the villages from the fifth column. In another directive issued in October the Regional Committee repeated similar instructions insisting on the destruction of those who disturb the mobilization of insurgents even by saying ''"wait, it's not the right moment yet"''.<ref>[http://www.montenegrina.net/pages/pages1/istorija/cg_u_2_svj_ratu/lijeve_greske_drugo_ime_za_zlocin.htm Dragutin Papović: “LIJEVE GREŠKE” – DRUGO IME ZA ZLOČIN], montenegrina.net; accessed 8 September 2018.</ref> Đilas himself wrote how retreating Partisans, who only punished their opponents in July, arbitrarily executed them following the Italian counteroffensive of August 1941.{{sfn|Lampe|2000|pg=214|ps=: "Milovan Djilas, the highest ranking Montenegrin in the Communist leadership, and Arso Jovanovic,...., were dispatched from Serbia to fan the scattered flames into a single bonfire. Only three weeks later an Italian division returned to put down the uprising and to turn loose their allies, the largely Turkish Sandžak Muslims, to loot and burn. Djilas himself described how the retreating Partisans now summarily executed any opponents, after merely punishing them in July."}}
From September 1941 onward, Communist Party program documents began to mention courts authorized to prescribe the death penalties. This immediately came to life in practice. Since October 1941, the headquarters of Partisan forces in Montenegro, Boka and Sandžak published lists of executed "enemies of the people, including spies and traitors" with a note - ''"to be continued..."''.<ref name="Vasović2009">{{cite book|last=Lakić|first=Zoran|authorlink= Zoran Lakić|title=Istorija Pljevalja|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n1zxZwEACAAJ|year=2009|publisher=Opština Pljevalja|page=371|chapter=Pljevlja 1941-1945<!-- |quote=.... у програмским документима КПЈ у којима се од септембра 1941. већ помињу “домаћи издајници”, народни судови који су имали право да изричу и смртне пресуде, што је заиста одмах потом заживјело у пракси...У Саопштењу Главног штаба народноослободилачких партизанских одреда за Црну Гору и Боку, која су почела да излазе у октобру 1941. објављивани су спискови ликвидираних “народних непријатеља, шпијуна и издајника уз назнаку - Наставиће се….и.-->}}</ref> During the first year the victims included women who "flirted" with Italians.<ref name="Đorđević 2000 14">{{cite book|last=Đorđević|first=Milinko|title=Sedam levih godina|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZlwtAQAAIAAJ|year=2000|publisher=Naš dom|page=14}}</ref> Most of the people killed by the communists in 1941 were military and administrative officers of former [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]] before the war.<ref name="Đorđević 2000 14"/> According to Croatian nationalist [[Jozo Tomasevich]], during the period of "leftist deviation" from circa December 1941 through May 1942, the Partisans, especially in Herzegovina and Montenegro, used terror against people who were not collaborating, but were potential class enemies.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|p=257}}
The Partisans occupied [[Kolašin]] in January and February 1942, and turned against all real and potential opposition, killing about 300 people and throwing their mangled corpses into pits they called the "dogs' cemetery". Due to this and other examples of communist terror, a part of Montenegrin population turned against the Partisans. According to ''Zbornik za istoriju'', "[a] land without Chetniks was suddenly overwhelmed by Chetniks", largely due to the policies of Left Deviations.<ref name="Лакић1981c">{{cite book|last=Лакић|first=Зоран|title=Народна власт у Црној Гори 1941–1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=emwNAAAAIAAJ|year=1981|publisher=Обод|page=250<!-- |quote=„Земља без четника одjеданпут доживљује праву четничку офанзиву". Овакво стање има објективних узрока, али је чињеница да га је убрзала политика „лијевих скретања", коза је довела до привременог пораза НОП-а у Црној Гори 1942. године ["A land without Chetniks suddenly lives trough a real Chetnik offensive." This situation is caused by many objective reasons, but it is a fact that it was accelerated by the policy of "left deviations". ] -->}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Zbornik za istoriju|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ObFdAAAAIAAJ|year=1970|publisher=Odeljenje za društvene nauke, Matica srpska|page=68|quote=Друга је ствар, међутим, као што констатује и ЦК КПЈ, да је политика левих скретања убрзала појаву четника, одвојила ... покрет и довела до његовог привременог разбијања у Црној Гори.}}</ref> Communist executions of notable tribal chieftains in Montenegro caused additional animosity of middle class peasants towards communists.<ref>{{cite book|title=Zbornik za istoriju|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ObFdAAAAIAAJ|year=1970|publisher=Odeljenje za društvene nauke, Matica srpska|page=68|quote= Ликвидације угледних братственика и племеника у Црној Гори изазивале су још веће сумње}}</ref> [[Pavle Đurišić|Đurišić]] soon recaptured Kolašin and held it as a [[Chetniks|Chetnik]] bastion until May 1943.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|pp=104–06}} His rule was marked by terrorizing Partisan supporters. A large number of captured Partisans and sympathizers were executed in following weeks, including lieutenant colonel Radisav Radević, major Batrić Zečević, captains Đuro Radosavljević, Mileta Lakićević and Tomica Jojić, and former member of Yugoslav Parliament Blagota Selić, none of which were members of the Communist Party. Đurišić formed a Chetnik prison in Kolašin, in which some 2,000 opponents were incarcerated and/or tortured.{{sfn|Bojović|1987|pp=52-53, 152-53}} Many were handed over to the Italians.{{sfn|Bojović|1987|pp=157-60}}
In March 1942, communists from [[Nikšić]] burned the villages of [[Ozrinići]] and Zagarač.<ref>{{cite book|title=Istorijski zapisi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u-nTAAAAMAAJ|year=1987|publisher=с.н.|page=119|quote=...спаљени Озринићи и Загарач, што је најдрастичнији примјер неправилног рада.}}</ref> According to some sources this was ordered by Đilas and [[Sava Kovačević]].<ref name="Miljanić1970">{{cite book|last=Miljanić|first=Gojko|title=Nikšićki NOP odred|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NWc-AAAAIAAJ|year=1970|publisher=Vojnoizdavaćki zavod|page=242|quote= Војо Шобајић, заменик комесара 1. ударног батаљона у својим сећањима пише да је од Милована Ђиласа добио писмо у коме се наређује да се потпуно спаси с. Озринићи. (Архив ОК Никшић 1/12 — Мемоарска грађа).}}</ref><ref name="Đuretić1997">{{cite book|last=Đuretić|first=Veselin|title=Violence against the Serb uprising|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j3riAAAAMAAJ|year=1997|publisher=Institut|page=274|quote=Делујући у том правцу, Милован Ђилас и Сава Ковачевић наредили су паљевину Озринића}}</ref> Between the onset of the [[Uprising in Montenegro (1941)|Uprising in Montenegro]] and the middle of 1942, communists killed between 500 and 624 people in Montenegro, most of them during armed conflict.{{sfn|Pavlićević|2012|p=14<!-- |ps=: "Dakle, ukupno je ubijeno u 1941. godini od početka ustanka do sredine 1942. godine, statistike se ne slažu, od 500 do 624 čovjeka" -->}}
==Serbia== In September 1941, Serb Partisans established the [[Republic of Užice]], a short-lived military mini-state with its administrative center in Užice. At the end of November 1941 Partisans were defeated and had to retreat from Serbia. The policy of leftist errors pursued by [[Josip Broz Tito]] substantially contributed to Partisan defeat in the Republic of Užice.{{sfn|Banac|1988|p=81<!-- |ps=: "This defeat stemmed in good part from the leftist policy pursued by Tito in the liberated territory centered on Uzice, ..." -->}} Because of the repression of the communists and their intention to carry on with communist revolution the population of Serbia also turned against the uprising and communist insurgents. At the beginning of December 1941<ref name="JelićStrugar1985">{{cite book|last1=Jelić|first1=Ivan|last2=Strugar|first2=Novak|title=War and revolution in Yugoslavia, 1941-1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zTWBAAAAIAAJ|year=1985|publisher=Socialist Thought and Practice|page=122|quote=Partisan Detachments of Yugoslavia and the leaderships of the national liberation movement withdrew from Serbia early in December 1941}}</ref> the communists moved from Serbia to Bosnia (nominally NDH) and joined their comrades who had already left Montenegro.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2002|p=147|ps=: "When repression burst the bubble of optimism, the popular mood in Serbia also turned against the insurgency and those who wanted to carry on with revolution... The partisan crossed into nominally NDH territory, where they joined up with their comrades who had left Montenegro."}}
==Herzegovina== In January and February 1942 alone, [[Yugoslav Partisans|Partisans]] executed 250 people in [[East Herzegovina|Eastern Herzegovina]] because they were accused of belonging to "fifth column".<ref>{{harvnb|Goldstein|2008|p=287}} {{lang|hr|"Samo u siječnju i veljači 1942. strijeljano je u istočnoj Hercegovini oko 250 ljudi, optuženih da pripadaju „petoj koloni”"}}</ref> In Herzegovina alone the total number of civilians murdered by communists in 1941–42 was probably around 500.{{sfn|Banac|1988|pp=82-83}}
Owing to "leftist errors" the Partisans were chased out of Herzegovina during the summer of 1942,<ref>{{cite book|last=Hamović|first=Miloš|title=Izbjeglištvo u Bosni i Hercegovini: 1941–1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S34tAQAAIAAJ|year=1994|publisher=Filip Višnjić|page=94|quote=Могло би се рећи да је епилог лијевог скретања у источној Херцеговини (и Црној Гори) био у томе што су домаће партизанске јединице биле принуђене да се повуку са тог простора и заједно са...}}</ref> not by the Axis forces but by its population.{{sfn|Strugar|1997|p=267<!-- |ps=: "... Dr. Savo Skoko ... konstatuje... da operativnu grupu NOV i POJ nisu u leto 1942 iz Hercegovine potisle nadmoćne snage okupatora već sam narod zbog grešaka prema njemu, kojima su presudno doprinela "leva skretanja"" -->}}
==Consequences== The policy of leftist deviation proved counterproductive.<ref name="Morrison2009">{{cite book|last=Morrison|first=Kenneth|title=Montenegro: a modern history|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xKMtAQAAIAAJ|year=2009|publisher=I.B. Tauris|isbn=978-1-84511-710-8|page=55}}</ref> Leftist deviation gave a real meaningful sense to the policy of those nationalists who found a way out of the difficult situation in collaboration with occupying and quisling forces.{{sfn|Strugar|1997|p=286<!-- |ps=: "Komunistički ekstremizam je davao realan smisao i onoj nacionalnoj politici koja je izlaz iz teške situacije nalazila u sporazumaštvu sa okupatorima, ustaško-domobranskim i drugim kvislinzima " -->}} "Red terror" antagonized most of the peasantry and angered the Soviet Union.<ref name="Bokovoy1998">{{cite book|last=Bokovoy|first=Melissa Katherine|title=Peasants and Communists: Politics and Ideology in the Yugoslav Countryside, 1941–1953|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p7DaAAAAMAAJ|year=1998|publisher=University of Pittsburgh Press|isbn=978-0-8229-4061-6|page=15|quote=The "red terror" had proved a disaster for KPJ. The Yugoslav Communists had not only alienated a large part of the peasantry, but also angered their International patron, Soviet Union.}}</ref> As a result of the communist actions, villagers from Eastern Herzegovina and Montenegro, who were far from being collaborators or [[kulak]]s, joined Chetnik forces en masse.{{sfn|Banac|1988|pg=82|ps=: "In the end, the red terror of 1941–1942 turned out to be a serious mistake. ... Terrorized peasants who were anything but collaborators or kulaks swelled the Chetnik ranks in Montenegro and Eastern Herzegovina."}}
==Propaganda== The songs and mottoes were composed to promote the policy of leftist deviations. The verse of one of them was: "Partisans, prepare machine guns, to greet the king and Englishmen"({{lang-sr|Партизани, спремите митраљезе да чекамо краља и Енглезе}}).<ref>{{cite book|title=Зборник за историју|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4ieGAAAAIAAJ|year=1971|publisher=Матица српска, Одељење за друштвене науке|page=60<!-- |quote=Лева скретања изражавају се кроз песму: „Партизани, спремите митраљезе да чекамо краља и Енглезе", или „Краљу Петре, ... -->}}</ref>{{sfn|Banac|1988|pp=82-83}} The Partisan slogan "[[Death to fascism, freedom to the people]]", a new greeting "Red Army is with us – the victory is ours!"{{sfn|Banac|1990|p=89}}
==Major exponents== [[File:Milovan Đilas.jpg|thumbnail|150px|[[Milovan Đilas]], one of the major exponents of the Leftist errors]] Major exponents of this policy included Milovan Đilas, [[Ivan Milutinović]] and [[Boris Kidrič]]. The Communist Party of Yugoslavia later publicly condemned this policy and punished (by warning them) several local commanders ([[Petar Drapšin]] and Miro Popara in Herzegovina and several Montenegrin party leaders).{{sfn|Banac|1988|pp=82-83}} Petar Drapšin was stripped of his rank, removed from all functions in the communist party and its membership.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hamović|first=Miloš|title=Izbjeglištvo u Bosni i Hercegovini: 1941–1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S34tAQAAIAAJ|year=1994|publisher=Filip Višnjić|page=94}}</ref> [[Moša Pijade]] was held responsible for the adoption of brutal extremist policy of the CPY.<ref name="PrestonPartridge2002a">{{cite book|last1=Preston|first1=Paul|authorlink1=Paul Preston|last2=Partridge|first2=Michael|last3=Smyth|first3=Denis|authorlink3=Denis Smyth|title=British documents on foreign affairs: reports and papers from the Foreign Office confidential print. From 1945 through 1950. Europe / editor, Denis Smyth|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E8yQAAAAMAAJ|year=2002|publisher=University Publications of America|isbn=978-1-55655-769-9|page=75|quote=He led the early and unsuccessful rising in Montenegro in 1941 and was at least partly responsible for the adoption of brutal and extremist methods.}}</ref>
In November 1941,<ref name="West2012">{{cite book|last=West|first=Richard|authorlink=Richard West (journalist)|title=Tito and the Rise and Fall of Yugoslavia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J34leeCdXFQC&pg=PT36|date=15 November 2012|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=978-0-571-28110-7|page=36}}</ref> Tito dismissed Milovan Đilas from the command of Partisan forces in Montenegro because of his mistakes during the uprising, including his "Leftist Errors".<ref name="Irvine1993">{{cite book|last=Irvine|first=Jill A.|title=The Croat Question: Partisan Politics in the Formation of the Yugoslav Socialist State|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gn9pAAAAMAAJ|year=1993|publisher=Westview Press|isbn=978-0-8133-8542-6|page=128|quote=Milovan Djilas, who had been removed from Montenego the previous fall for his "leftist errors, ..."}}</ref>
Tito claimed Đilas made mistakes because he organized a frontal struggle of armies against a much stronger enemy instead of connecting the Partisan struggle with the people's uprising and adopting the partisan methods of resistance. Đilas was appointed as editor of the paper ''[[Borba (newspaper)|Borba]]'', the Party's main propaganda organ.{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=152}} While Tito repeatedly accused other communist officials from Montenegro for "[[sectarianism]]", Edvard Kardelj {{Who|date=September 2018}} admitted to Đilas that ''"grave sectarian errors were made in Serbia in 1941"'' (under Tito's administration).{{sfn|Swain|2010|p=47<!-- |ps=: "Although Tito never repudiated his policies in Užice and Foča, and always directed the charges against "sectarianism" against the actions of others in Montenegro, Kardelj conceded in an unguarded conversation with Đilas that "grave sectarian errors were made in Serbia in 1941"" -->}}
